	<dd><a name="comment_1077" ></a>
	<p><em><strong>Gavin</strong> replies:</em> Yes, it's interesting that all these people who have no interest in politics and are just lazy idiots somehow manage to find a site on the internet that is entirely about politics and take the time to comment on their considered reasons for choosing not to vote. "Apathy" requires that you do not care and do not have an opinion. Anyone who has constructed a considered reason for making the entirely legitimate choice not to vote is not apathetic or lazy. Additionally, other people's reasoning and comments may even change some people's minds. Those who are apathetic about politics will obviously have no interest in this site.</p>
	<small>
	written 18th Apr 2005 <!-- | <a
    href="/abuse/?postid=841&amp;commentid=1077">abusive?</a>
    --> </small>
	</dd>
	<dd><a name="comment_1203" ></a>
	<p><em><strong>original poster</strong> replies:</em> Gavin, very fair points - indeed my first post seems a little crass (with the benefit of hindsight) However, I fear that for every politically engaged non voter, there are a hundred who do deserve a gentle ribbing. For the few who do provide "a considered reason for making the entirely legitimate choice not to vote" then I salute your noble (if futile) gesture - indeed you have provided me with a good deal to think about. Yet the majority post a single trivial and oft bizarre reason to avoid voting. Leaving the impression that its been seized upon as an excuse to avoid actually thinking about politics. "they is all the same man, innit" "i forgot to register to vote, its not my fault" etc, etc </p>
	<small>
